embedding similarity based retrieval is far more slop prone than simclustering, but it always maxes click through rates. algo catches you clicking on one slop, decides to surface all slop of that nature from across the world

machine intelligence first impacts the physical world via the costs of on-land logistics being driven significantly lower via autonomous cars and trucks. the current miracle of global production logic is driven by moving massive tonnage on giant cargo ships, with tiny crews, very efficiently. packaged goods are shipped transcontinenally ~multiple times before reaching American consumers 

with autonomous electric logistics you have trucks that can move much smaller loads on the last mile very cheaply (and perhaps more important, can engage with zero latency). we may find that intermediate production becomes more distributed over land rather than just over sea. factories and production facilities are spaced out according to land use efficiency with software defined cargo streams between them. ironically this may create more local jobs in the interim

while large scale autonomous warehousing has become common for walmart, amazon, etc you’d expect to see far more distributed nodes with an extreme explosion of local SKUs, and final construction closer to the site of demand. you would also expect the idea of returns, exchanges, etc becoming significantly easier and cheaper. ownership and purchase decisions of expensive things may begin to feel different

overall, massive containership ocean freight will continue to dominate just due to the simple laws of physics of friction over water vs over roads and so on. but expect far less friction for over land logistics
because the crew cost of shipping is completely negligible vs fuel costs etc
